title: For Sale:  Selling Hand-Cast 9mm/380 Auto, 40 S&W/10mm, and 45 ACP/Colt Bullet Tips
location: Fort Leonard Wood, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent: Hello!I am selling .356 (9mm/380 auto), .401 (40 S&W/10mm), and .451/.452 (45 ACP/Colt) bullet tips (boolits), whichever you prefer. I cast them by hand and inspect each one myself so you can be assured you're not getting something screwy from someone not paying attention. Just to emphasize, these are only the bullet TIPS (often called boolits). You can use these to load your own cartidges. I use these in my own bullets I load and have better results than off-the-shelf walmart ammo. Obviously it will also depend on what powder, etc. you use, but that's not hard to figure out if you don't already have a preferred formula.I do have written confirmation from the Program Manager (IOI) at the Firearms Industry Programs Branch here in MO that these are perfectly legal to make and sell without an FFL, so there are no laws being broken here (always a plus).The basic "package", per se, would be simply cast and sold. I can however size and lube if you'd like. I powder coat mine for my own personal use, so I don't keep a lot of lube on hand, but I can order it without an issue if you can't provide it. Sizing & Lubing adds a very minor amount extra. Pricing is as follows..356, 100ct. - $7.00(Round nose, 124gr. mold - weighs roughly 131gr. with my alloy).356, 1,000ct. - $60.00(Round nose, 124gr. mold - weighs roughly 131gr. with my alloy).356, 100ct. sized & lubed - $8.00(Round nose, 124gr. mold - weighs roughly 131gr. with my alloy).356, 1,000ct. sized & lubed - $70.00(Round nose, 124gr. mold - weighs roughly 131gr. with my alloy).401, 100ct. - $8.50(Truncated cone, 175gr. mold - weighs roughly 185gr. with my alloy).401, 1,000ct. - $75.00(Truncated cone, 175gr. mold - weighs roughly 185gr. with my alloy).401, 100ct. sized & lubed - $9.50(Truncated cone, 175gr. mold - weighs roughly 185gr. with my alloy).401 1,000ct. sized & lubed - $85.00(Truncated cone, 175gr. mold - weighs roughly 185gr. with my alloy).451, 100ct. sized & lubed - $10.50(Round nose, 230gr. mold - weighs roughly 240gr. with my alloy).451, 1,000ct. sized & lubed - $95.00(Round nose, 230gr. mold - weighs roughly 240gr. with my alloy).452, 100ct. - $9.50(Round nose, 230gr. mold - weighs roughly 243gr. with my alloy).452, 1,000ct. - $85.00(Round nose, 230gr. mold - weighs roughly 243gr. with my alloy).452, 100ct. sized & lubed - $10.50(Round nose, 230gr. mold - weighs roughly 243gr. with my alloy).452, 1,000ct. sized & lubed - $95.00(Round nose, 230gr. mold - weighs roughly 243gr. with my alloy)Please note: The more you buy the more you will save.If you are looking for other amounts, 500ct, 10,000ct. etc. let me know and I should be able to work with you and still keep your cost down.I am located in St. Robert, MO and can meet anyone for sales, etc. However, if you'd like me to ship, I can do that also (at cost). I have talked with just about every person in California (yes, the state) and as long as it's just the lead tips they don't mind the shipping across state lines. Other states may vary, but generally speaking CA is the hardest to work with.Shipping can be had for roughly $6-7. The amount that will fit in the box will vary depending on bullet size. .356 is roughly 900 per box, .452 is roughly 600 per box.Please note, if you are looking for a different bullet size, let me know. I may be able to work something out for you (I have for others).Please contact me at REDACTED. Text or call.Thank you!-Joseph

title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington Model 10 12 Gauge Pump Nickel
postcontent: For sale is a Remington Model 10 chambered for 12 gauge 2 3/4 inch shells. It's a takedown gun that loads and ejects from the bottom, and it doesn't have a trigger disconnector, so it'll slamfire through all 5+1 shells it can hold - all you have to do is hold the trigger down and pump. There's a reason why they used them as trench guns in the first World War!It's an uncommon and distinctive old shotgun with a lot of character. The previous owner(s?) cut the barrel back to 23 inches and nickeled it, but the work was done well - the barrel is nicely crowned and the bead is centered. The finish has held up remarkably well for a gun this old, with just a couple spots where it's wearing through. The serial puts the date of manufacture at 1924. While it has a little bit of wear and tear, the action is reasonbly smooth and the gun is mechanically fine. It's certainly a shooter. You don't see these very often and this is an exceptionally unique one, it definitely has that prohibition era style to it. I'm not really looking for a trade but I'm open to offers.Feel free to email me for more pictures or any questions.

title: For Sale:  Beware Scammer/illegal activity selling Glock 26 and Ruger 10/22
postcontent: Beware to all that the guy who posted a Glock 26 for $250 and a Ruger 10/22 for $150 is scamming and/or participating in illegal activity. He is claiming to be out of state in Louisiana (with a California number) and that he will ship the guns via usps to you once he receives payment through wall mart. First of all, it is illegal to ship handguns from an unlicensed (non-ffl) to another non-licensed person unless they are in the same state. Being that he is claiming to ship a handgun from one state to another, person to person, is a federal violation. Furthermore, he is offering to ship via USPS, which isn't allowed to take handguns unless you are an ffl. (Ups and fed-ex can still). Be on on the lookout for ads with the number REDACTED. His name he claims in James Lafitte, claiming to live in Slidell, Louisiana. I have also seen similar posts on other sites with guns for ridiculously low prices, most likely so he can get people to forget the laws and send money without thinking that he might just take the money and run.
